-- State Bank of India raises $1.28 bln via share sale 
-- By Sumeet Chatterjee
-- Thu Jan 30, 2014 10:35PM EST
-- None



MUMBAI, Jan 31 (Reuters) - State Bank of India Ltd <SBI.NS>, the country's largest lender, said it has raised 80.32 billion rupees ($1.28 billion) through a sale of shares to institutional investors to boost its capital requirements.

The proceeds from the share sale will increase the overall capital adequacy ratio of the state-run bank to 12.81 percent  and tier one capital adequacy ratio to over 9.67 percent, SBI said in a statement late on Thursday. SBI launched the share offering on Tuesday in the indicative price band of 1,565-1,596 rupees a share to raise as much as $1.5 billion. The bank sold 51.3 million shares in the offering at the lower end of the range.